Section 1:
1 L.D. 1726
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 ENERGY, UTILITIES AND TECHNOLOGY
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1153, L.D. 1726, “An Act to Enhance
10 the Coordination and Effectiveness of Integrated Distribution Grid Planning”
11 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
12 following:
13 'Sec. 1. 2 MRSA §9, sub-§3, ¶D-1 is enacted to read:
14 D-1. When possible, seek to ensure consistency in energy planning and analysis,
15 including, but not limited to, through the use, in all energy planning and analysis
16 conducted by the office, of an energy forecasting method consistent with the method
17 used by the office in preparing the comprehensive state energy plan as required by
18 paragraph C. The office shall ensure that the energy forecasting methodology used in
19 preparing the comprehensive state energy plan is made available for use by other state
20 agencies;
21 Sec. 2. 35-A MRSA §3147, sub-§1, ¶A-1 is enacted to read:
22 A-1. "Advanced conductor" means an electrical conductor that has a direct current
23 electrical resistance at least 10% lower than existing conductors of a similar diameter
24 on the electric system.
25 Sec. 3. 35-A MRSA §3147, sub-§1, ¶B-1 is enacted to read:
26 B-1. "Grid-enhancing technology" has the same meaning as in section 3148,
27 subsection 1, paragraph A.
28 Sec. 4. 35-A MRSA §3147, sub-§4, ¶D, as enacted by PL 2021, c. 702, §8, is
29 amended to read:
30 D. Include, at a minimum, the following:
31 (1) Forecasts of projected load, including forecasts of end-use electrification,
32 energy efficiency and distributed energy resources and, when appropriate,
33 consideration of the energy forecasting method used to prepare the comprehensive
34 state energy plan required pursuant to Title 2, section 9, subsection 3, paragraph C;
Page 1 - 132LR0881(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1153, L.D. 1726
1 (2) Baseline energy supply data and assessments, including but not limited to
2 planned generation retirements; new generation that is planned or needed,
3 including generation of electricity from renewable sources; and energy storage
4 installations;
5 (3) Analysis of hosting capacity, including locational benefits of distributed
6 energy resources and areas of existing or potential system congestion;
7 (4) Analysis of available and emerging technologies necessary to enable load
8 management and flexibility and those technologies necessary to improve efficiency
9 and reliability of and reduce congestion of the grid, including, but not limited to,
10 the use of advanced conductors and grid-enhancing technologies, taking into
11 consideration the commission's review pursuant to section 3148;
12 (5) An assessment of the environmental, equity and environmental justice impacts
13 of grid plans; and
14 (6) An identification of cost-effective near-term grid investments and operations
15 needed to achieve the priorities identified in subsection 2; and
16 (7) Consideration of the use of low-voltage sensors to improve grid monitoring
17 capacity, including data related to grid power quality, transformer status and
18 distributed energy resource capacity by location; and
19 Sec. 5. 35-A MRSA §3147, sub-§4, as enacted by PL 2021, c. 702, §8, is amended
20 by amending the first blocked paragraph to read:
21 The commission shall make the filing for each covered utility available for public comment
22 for a period of no less than 60 days. The commission may order a covered utility to revise
23 the filing to address any deficiencies. The commission may use the filing and the input
24 received from interested parties in rate cases or other proceedings involving the covered
25 utility. In a competitive solicitation conducted by the commission, the commission may
26 use the filings submitted pursuant to this subsection to develop requests for proposals,
27 evaluate bids and negotiate agreements in order to optimize grid capacity.
28 Sec. 6. Assessment of nonwires alternative process. In consultation with the
29 Efficiency Maine Trust and the Office of the Public Advocate, the Public Utilities
30 Commission shall conduct a review of the nonwires alternative investigation and
31 recommendation process established in the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 35-A, section
32 3132-C. The commission's review must assess the efficiency of that process and consider
33 how that process is incorporated into integrated grid plan filings submitted by large
34 investor-owned transmission and distribution utilities in accordance with the requirements
35 established by Title 35-A, section 3147. The review must include the opportunity for
36 stakeholders to provide comments to the commission. The commission shall develop
37 recommendations for changes to the nonwires alternative investigation and
38 recommendation process based on its review, which may include recommended legislation
39 to better integrate nonwires alternatives into the requirements for grid plan filings. By
40 March 1, 2026, the commission shall provide a report of its recommendations to the Joint
41 Standing Committee on Energy, Utilities and Technology. The committee may report out
42 a bill related to the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.
43 Sec. 7. Flexible interconnection; evaluation; reports. The Public Utilities
44 Commission shall explore and evaluate the feasibility of adopting emerging flexible
Page 2 - 132LR0881(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1153, L.D. 1726
415 interconnection options in order to use distributed energy resources, increase grid capacity,
426 decrease grid instability and reduce costs in achieving state goals related to clean energy,
437 including energy storage and beneficial electrification. In exploring and evaluating flexible
448 interconnection options, the commission shall:
5 1. Review potential practices for providing flexible interconnection options;
6 2. Engage with stakeholders, including members of the interconnection working group
7 established pursuant to Public Law 2023, chapter 307, section 8;
8 3. Identify any barriers to adopting flexible interconnection options;
9 4. Identify ways in which customers seeking connection might benefit from flexible
10 interconnection processes; and
11 5. Determine whether the costs of flexible interconnection may affect
12 noninterconnecting customers and how that may be mitigated.
13 By February 15, 2026, the commission shall submit an initial report summarizing the
14 commission's activities under this section to the Joint Standing Committee on Energy,
15 Utilities and Technology. After reviewing the initial report, the committee may report out
16 a bill relating to the report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature. By
17 February 15, 2027, the commission shall submit a final report to the joint standing
18 committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over energy and utility matters that
19 includes the commission's evaluation of flexible interconnection options, along with any
20 recommendations. After reviewing the final report, the committee may report out a bill
21 related to the report to the 133rd Legislature in 2027.
22 Sec. 8. Effective date. Those sections of this Act that enact the Maine Revised
23 Statutes, Title 35-A, section 3147, subsection 1, paragraphs A-1 and B-1 and that amend
24 Title 35-A, section 3147, subsection 4 take effect February 1, 2026.'
25 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
26 number to read consecutively.
27 SUMMARY
2288 This amendment replaces the bill. It does the following.
29 1. It requires the Governor's Energy Office to seek to ensure consistency in energy
30 planning and analysis, including through the use of an energy forecasting method consistent
31 with the method used by the office in preparing the comprehensive state energy plan.
32 2. It requires grid plans filed by certain transmission and distribution utilities to, when
33 appropriate, consider the energy forecasting method used to prepare the comprehensive
34 state energy plan. It also specifies that available and emerging technologies, which must
35 be analyzed in the grid plan filing, include the use of advanced conductors and grid-
36 enhancing technologies, and the amendment defines these terms. The amendment also
37 requires that utility grid plan filings include consideration of the use of low-voltage sensors
38 to improve grid monitoring capacity. These changes to the grid plan filing requirements
39 take effect February 1, 2026.
40 3. It allows the Public Utilities Commission, in a competitive solicitation, to use grid
41 plan filings to develop requests for proposals, evaluate bids and negotiate agreements in
42 order to optimize grid capacity.
Page 3 - 132LR0881(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 1153, L.D. 1726
1 4. It requires the commission, in consultation with the Efficiency Maine Trust and the
2 Office of the Public Advocate, to conduct a review of the nonwires alternative investigation
3 and recommendation process established in the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 35-A, section
4 3132-C. By March 1, 2026, the commission must provide a report of its recommendations
5 to the Joint Standing Committee on Energy, Utilities and Technology.
6 5. It requires the commission to explore and evaluate the feasibility of adopting
7 emerging flexible interconnection options in order to use distributed energy resources,
8 increase grid capacity, decrease grid instability and reduce costs. By February 15, 2026,
9 the commission must submit an initial report summarizing the commission's activities and,
10 by February 15, 2027, the commission must submit a final report to the joint standing
11 committee of the Legislature having jurisdiction over energy and utility matters.
1122 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
1133 (See attached)
